            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Schmidt is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog-belt, born and raised in the quiet, residential blocks of the Sunset District. Her father was a mechanic whose knuckles were permanently stained with grease, and her mother juggled shifts as a waitress at a diner on Irving Street. Life was practical, not aspirational. For Heather, Lowell High School was a social requirement to be endured, not an academic launchpad. She graduated in the mid-90s with a diploma, a pack-a-day habit she\u2019d later kick, and no clear path forward.\n\nFor nearly a decade, she drifted through a series of service jobs that paid the bills but chipped away at her spirit: stocking shelves at a grocery store, serving lukewarm coffee to tourists, and folding sweaters at a department store in the Stonestown Galleria. The turning point came at 28, during a particularly bleak winter. Laid off from her retail job, she was complaining to her cousin, a city plumber, who bluntly advised, \"Go drive for Muni. It's a union gig. You'll be set.\" The idea was terrifying but practical. After a rigorous training period that tested her patience and nerve, Heather earned her operator\u2019s badge. She felt a surge of pride she hadn't experienced since she was a kid.\n\nNow, at 45, Heather has been driving the city\u2019s arteries for over 15 years. Her commute is a 5.5-mile bus ride from her small, tidy condo in the Outer Richmond to the Kirkland bus yard. Divorced in her late thirties, she has built a life of sturdy independence. Her social circle is a tight-knit group of fellow operators who share dark humor and an unshakeable bond forged over navigating downtown traffic and difficult passengers.\n\nFrom her driver's seat, Heather has a unique vantage point on San Francisco's evolution. She\u2019s watched tech booms reshape the skyline and neighborhoods gentrify block by block. She serves a patchwork quilt of humanity daily\u2014the elderly woman on her way to Chinatown, the tech bro with his headphones, the homeless person seeking a warm seat. Her dream isn\u2019t grand; it\u2019s tangible. She wants to pay off her mortgage, retire with her full pension, and maybe one day take a long trip to see the national parks. Heather Schmidt is the city\u2019s steady pulse, an unsung anchor in a place constantly reinventing itself."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers the smell of her father's hands\u2014a permanent perfume of motor oil and metal dust. At seven, after she fell and bent her bike's front wheel, he carried it into his garage. She watched his grease-stained knuckles work with surprising gentleness, coaxing the metal back into alignment. He left a perfect, dark thumbprint on the clean silver handlebar. To her, that mark wasn't dirt; it was the physical proof of a father\u2019s quiet, capable love. It taught her that real value came from fixing what was broken.\n\n2.\nAt 28, facing a wall of identical beige sweaters at Stonestown, a wave of cold panic washed over her. The scent of recycled air and cheap perfume felt suffocating. For a single, crystal-clear moment while refolding a sleeve for the tenth time, she saw her future: an endless series of meaningless, repetitive tasks. This quiet desperation, felt under the harsh fluorescent lights, was the final push she needed. It wasn't the layoff that changed her life; it was the terrifying realization that she was becoming as blank and folded as the sweaters.\n\n3.\nHer first solo run on the 38-Geary, just after earning her badge at 29. Her hands gripped the massive steering wheel so tightly her knuckles were white. The hiss of the hydraulic doors opening for her first passenger felt like a cannon shot. As she pulled away from the curb, navigating the lumbering vehicle through traffic, a feeling of deep, profound competence settled over her fear. It wasn't a job; she was piloting a vital piece of the city. That day, she stopped drifting and started driving.\n\n4.\nFor two years, a tiny, immaculately dressed woman with a floral silk scarf got on her bus every Wednesday morning at 22nd Avenue, riding to Chinatown. They never spoke, but they shared a ritual: a slight, formal nod. One week, she wasn't there. Or the next. Heather kept watching for her at that stop for months, a small, unanswered question on her daily route. The absence taught her how intimately she was tied to the city's quiet routines and the silent stories of its people.\n\n5.\nThe rainy Tuesday after her husband moved out, around age 38, she almost called in sick. Instead, she took her shift. Behind the wheel, the city lights streaking across her massive windshield, she found a strange peace. Each stop, each timed green light, was a predictable anchor in the storm of her life. The rumble of the engine was a steady heartbeat when her own felt erratic. That night, her bus wasn't just a vehicle; it was her armored shell, proof that she alone was enough to keep herself moving forward."
